Recursive Bubble Sort Notes
Definition

Recursive Bubble Sort is a recursive version of Bubble Sort where recursion replaces the outer loop.

In each recursive call:

One complete pass is performed.
The largest element moves to its correct position at the end.
The remaining unsorted part (n - 1 elements) is sorted recursively.
Code
class Solution {
    public void bS(int[] arr, int n) {
        if(n == 1) return;

        for(int j = 0; j <= n - 2; j++) {
            if(arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }

        bS(arr, n - 1);
    }

    public int[] bubbleSort(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        bS(nums, n);
        return nums;
    }
}
Intuition

Bubble Sort works by pushing the largest element to the end during each pass.

Instead of using an outer loop:

for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)

we recursively sort the first n-1 elements after every pass.

Recursive Flow
Base Case
if(n == 1) return;

When only one element remains, the array is already sorted.

One Bubble Pass
for(int j = 0; j <= n - 2; j++)

Compare adjacent elements:

if(arr[j] > arr[j + 1])

Swap them if they are in the wrong order.

After this loop:

Largest element among first n elements
moves to index n-1
Recursive Call
bS(arr, n - 1);

Now sort the remaining unsorted part.

Dry Run
Input
[5, 3, 1, 4]
First Call
bS(arr, 4)

Pass:

5 3 1 4
↓
3 5 1 4
↓
3 1 5 4
↓
3 1 4 5

Largest element (5) reaches the end.

Recursive call:

bS(arr, 3)
Second Call

Pass on first 3 elements:

3 1 4 5
↓
1 3 4 5

Recursive call:

bS(arr, 2)
Third Call

Pass on first 2 elements:

1 3 4 5

Recursive call:

bS(arr, 1)
Base Case
n == 1

Return.

Final Array:

[1, 3, 4, 5]
Recursion Tree
bS(arr,4)
    |
    └── bS(arr,3)
            |
            └── bS(arr,2)
                    |
                    └── bS(arr,1)
                            |
                          Return
Time Complexity
Worst Case
O(n²)

Comparisons:

(n-1) + (n-2) + (n-3) + ... + 1
= n(n-1)/2
= O(n²)
Average Case
O(n²)
Best Case
O(n²)

(No optimization for early stopping is used.)

Space Complexity
Recursive Stack Space
O(n)

Because there are n recursive calls.

Auxiliary Space
O(1)

No extra array is used.

Key Observations

✅ Recursion replaces the outer loop.

✅ After every recursive call, one element is fixed at its correct position.

✅ Largest element moves to the end during each pass.

✅ Sorting is performed in-place.

✅ Stable Sorting Algorithm.

Interview Point

Iterative Bubble Sort

Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)

Recursive Bubble Sort

Time: O(n²)
Space: O(n) (due to recursion stack)

Recursive Bubble Sort is mainly used to understand recursion and is rarely preferred in production because it uses extra stack space.